== Generalized creation and annihilation operators ==


Thanks to representation theory and C*-algebras the operators derived above are actually a specific instance of a more generalized notion of creation and annihilation operators in the context of CCR and CAR algebras. Mathematically and even more generally ladder operators can be understood in the context of a root system of a semisimple Lie group and the associated semisimple Lie algebra without the need of realizing the representation as operators on a functional Hilbert space.

In the Hilbert space representation case the operators are constructed as follows: Let formula_63 be a one-particle Hilbert space (that is, any Hilbert space, viewed as representing the state of a single particle).
The (bosonic) CCR algebra over formula_63 is the algebra-with-conjugation-operator (called &quot;*&quot;) abstractly generated by elements formula_65, where formula_66ranges freely over formula_63, subject to the relations

formula_68
in bra–ket notation.

The map formula_69 from formula_63 to the bosonic CCR algebra is required to be complex antilinear (this adds more relations). Its adjoint is formula_71, and the map formula_72 is complex linear in . Thus formula_63 embeds as a complex vector subspace of its own CCR algebra. In a representation of this algebra, the element formula_65 will be realized as an annihilation operator, and formula_71 as a creation operator.

In general, the CCR algebra is infinite dimensional. If we take a Banach space completion, it becomes a C*-algebra. The CCR algebra over formula_63 is closely related to, but not identical to, a Weyl algebra.

For fermions, the (fermionic) CAR algebra over formula_63 is constructed similarly, but using anticommutator relations instead, namely

formula_78

The CAR algebra is finite dimensional only if formula_63 is finite dimensional. If we take a Banach space completion (only necessary in the infinite dimensional case), it becomes a formula_80 algebra. The CAR algebra is closely related, but not identical to, a Clifford algebra.
Physically speaking, formula_65 removes (i.e. annihilates) a particle in the state formula_82 whereas formula_71 creates a particle in the state formula_82.

The free field vacuum state is the state formula_85 with no particles, characterized by
formula_86

If formula_82 is normalized so that formula_88, then formula_89 gives the number of particles in the state formula_82.

== Creation and annihilation operators for reaction-diffusion equations ==
The annihilation and creation operator description has also been useful to analyze classical reaction diffusion equations, such as the situation when a gas of molecules formula_91 diffuse and interact on contact, forming an inert product: formula_92. To see how this kind of reaction can be described by the annihilation and creation operator formalism, consider formula_93 particles at a site on a one dimensional lattice. Each particle moves to the right or left with a certain probability, and each pair of particles at the same site annihilates each other with a certain other probability.

The probability that one particle leaves the site during the short time period &#x27; is proportional to formula_94, let us say a probability formula_95 to hop left and formula_96 to hop right. All formula_97 particles will stay put with a probability formula_98. (Since &#x27; is so short, the probability that two or more will leave during is very small and will be ignored.)

We can now describe the occupation of particles on the lattice as a &#x27;ket&#x27; of the form formula_99. It represents the juxtaposition (or conjunction, or tensor product) of the number states formula_100 formula_101, formula_102 located at the individual sites of the lattice. Recall that

